tweet: My vote today is a vote for much needed reconciliation and hope that together we can heal our country. Let’s work side-by-side, seeking common ground, to usher in a bright future for the American people, our country, and our nation.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: A house divided cannot stand. And today we are divided. Fragmentation and polarity are ripping our country apart.  This breaks my heart, and breaks the hearts of all patriotic Americans, whether we are Democrats, Republicans, or Independents.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: The Founders of our country made clear their concerns about impeachment being a purely partisan exercise. In the Federalist Papers, Alexander Hamilton warned against any impeachment that would merely “connect itself with the pre-existing factions,” and...

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: On the other side — The president’s opponents insist that if we do not impeach, our country will collapse into dictatorship. All but explicitly, they accuse him of treason. Such extreme rhetoric was never conducive to an impartial fact-finding process.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: On the one side: The president’s defenders insist that he has done nothing wrong. They agree with the absurd proclamation that his conduct was “perfect.” They have abdicated their responsibility to exercise legitimate oversight, and instead do the bidding of their party’s leader.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: When I cast my vote in support of the impeachment inquiry nearly three months ago, I said that in order to maintain the integrity of this solemn undertaking, it must not be a partisan endeavor. Tragically, that’s what it has been.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: I also could not in good conscience vote for impeachment because removal of a sitting President must not be the culmination of a partisan process, fueled by tribal animosities that have so gravely divided our country.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸

I am standing in the center and have decided to vote Present.

tweet: We realized that everyone around us was sympathetic to the Palestinian protestors and that it was tear gas being fired, not live rounds. Still, the tension was high and our cabbie started yelling about how the Israelis wanted to start another intifada.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: Jerusalem — shortly after praying for peace at the Kotel, Western Wall, I visited the Mount of Olives. I was with one of my best friends from growing up in Maryland, & we took a cab up the steep hill. Suddenly, we heard shots fired and saw smoke rising from the Dome of the Rock.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: It was the only time in Iraq I had to point my rifle at people and earnestly tell them to back off. The tension ended as quickly as it started as more Marines arrived. Still, it’s one of the memories that makes me wonder about the randomness of life & how we occupy space & time.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet:
We went to the homes where the rockets hit, and I was taking photos when my squad left me to move to the next house. I suddenly found myself surrounded by angry Iraqis. 

It was 13 years ago, but it feels like yesterday, minutes of my life etched in stone.

name: Cullen Tiernan 🇺🇸
tweet: Hit, Iraq — when I was patrolling with the 22ND Marine Expeditionary Unit, we had rockets shot at us. They missed. Still, they flew directly over our heads and into people’s homes, tragically killing two civilians.
